Rosogolla has many varieties… but the one that tops my list is Nolen Gur Rosogolla 🤍

Nolen gur literally means new jaggery, It’s sweetness isn’t just sweet… it has notes of toffee, dark caramel, and that thodi si bitter undertone that makes it irresistible 🤌🏽
Soft, Spongy, Melt-in-the-mouth 🤤
Honestly, this is one of the best rosogolla’s you’ll ever have ✨

Some of my most memorable food experiences, across places and cultures 😍
Wherever I go, food always becomes my biggest inspiration. It’s never just about eating, it’s about watching, learning, understanding the culture behind it.

Japan was a real eye-opener for me. From steaming hot gyoza to watching an 80-year-old chef make tempura right in front of me, showing me exactly how it should be eaten. That kind of respect for food stays with you 🍤
Italy was pure joy. My first gelato, Fior di Latte. Just milk, done right. Simple, honest, unforgettable 🍦

And then closer home, Pune. That kala mutton at Jagdambh. So powerful, so rooted, I had to come back and recreate it on YFL. And the love it received said everything ❤️

India will always be unmatched, but these journeys across kitchens and cultures have taught me so much.
Loved sharing these stories with Gulshan Devaiyah.
Because no matter where I go, food is always the starting point. ✈️🍽️

That said, there are smarter swaps you can make 💡

You need to ‘FIX YOUR OIL!!’ 🤔

Ever wondered why some dishes taste extra good? It’s the oil 😉
Oil is a flavour magnet, so when it’s pure, your food gets richer aroma, better taste and real nutrients. Unlike most of the refined oils that go through harsh processing. On the other hand ‘Cold Pressed Oils’ keep it simple and natural.

That’s why Tata Simply Better Cold Pressed Oils are my go-to, natural, hexane-free, flavourful and perfect for everyday cooking. Every bottle has its own personality and works beautifully across multiple dishes ✨

If you want a list of which oil suits which recipe, comment “Simply better” and I’ll send it to you personally 💛

#TataSimplyBetter #Unrefined #Coldpressed

60-Minute vs 3 Hour vs 12 Hour DAL MAKHANI Series EP 3 | Chef Sanjyot Keer
This is the 12-hour slow-cooked version - the finale of my exclusive Facebook series! 🔥
This is how Dal Makhani was traditionally made, back when people had the patience and the skill to use the tandoor’s residual heat at night for better fuel efficiency.
The result? A magical, melt-in-mouth Dal Makhani.

A gentle coal fire.
A pot that barely bubbles.
Hours of starch breaking down naturally.
By morning, the dal turns silky, dark, and almost glossy on its own.
Same ingredients as Episode 1, but the texture, aroma, and richness are on another level.

To wrap the series, I compare all three! The 60-minute, the 3-hour, and the 12-hour version. 🔥

Time changes Dal Makhani in ways you have to taste to believe.
Would you ever try cooking Dal Makhani for over 12 hours?

Get ready to enjoy the soft and delicate flavours of this delicious 'Ice Halwa'!! 👌

ICE HALWA

Ingredients

A generous pinch of roasted saffron
½ cup +2 tbsps milk
½ cup ghee
½ cup refined flour (maida)
½ cup castor sugar
Almond flakes to sprinkle
Pistachio powder to sprinkle

Method

1. Crush roasted saffron coarsely. Add 2 tbsps milk and mix well.
2. Heat a nonstick kadai. Add remaining milk and once it becomes warm, add ghee and refined flour and cook for 3-4 minutes or till the mixture is thick.
3. Add castor sugar and cook till the mixture starts to leave the sides of the pan. 
4. Add saffron milk and mix well.
5. Take a plate and spread little mixture on it. After cooling, if it easily gets rolled and doesn’t stick to your hands, the mixture is ready. 
6. Take a piece of butter paper, spread the mixture, keep another piece of butter paper in top and roll into thin sheet with the help of a rolling pin. 
7. Sprinkle almond flakes, pistachio powder and roll a rolling pin lightly. Air dry for 2 days.
8. Cut into squares and serve.

When Kerala's rich spices and tender mutton meet, you get a curry that’s not just food, but a journey of flavours.

Which curry should I make next? Let me know in the comments.

Recipe: 

Ingredients
750 grams mutton, cut into 2-inch pieces on the bone
2-3 tbsps oil
½ tsp fenugreek seeds (methi dana)
4-5 green cardamoms
2 medium onions, sliced
2 green chillies, chopped
1 tbsp chopped garlic
¼ tsp turmeric powder
1 tsp red chilli powder
½ tsp black pepper powder
1 tsp cumin powder
2 tsps coriander powder
2 medium tomatoes, chopped
10-15 curry leaves
Salt to taste
½ tsp garam masala powder
2-3 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves
Fried curry leaf sprig for garnish
Red rice for serving

Method
1. Heat oil in a kadai. Add fenugreek seeds and green cardamoms and sauté till fragrant.
2. Add onions and sauté till golden brown.
3. Add green chillies and garlic and sauté for a minute.
4. Add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, black pepper powder, cumin powder and coriander powder and sauté for 30 seconds.
5. Add tomatoes and cook till pulpy.
6. Add curry leaves, mutton, salt and sear on high heat for 6-8 minutes.
7. Add garam masala powder, 3 cups water and cook on medium heat for 40-45 minutes.
8. Add coriander and mix well. 
9. Transfer in a serving bowl, garnish with fried curry leaf sprig and serve hot with red rice.

Thukpa banate waqt sabse acchi baat kya hoti hai?
Speed aur flavour ka perfect balance. 
Toh aap kab bana rahe ho?

Recipe:

Ingredients
200 grams noodles, boiled
1 inch ginger, roughly chopped
6-8 garlic cloves
10-15 coriander stems
3-4 fresh red chillies, stemmed
1 medium tomato, roughly chopped
1 medium onion, roughly chopped
1 tbsp oil
3 cups vegetable stock
¼ medium cabbage, shredded
1 medium carrot, peeled and sliced
4-5 button mushrooms, sliced
6-8 French beans, thinly sliced
Salt to taste
1 tsp vinegar
Sesame oil to drizzle
Chilli oil to drizzle
Thinly sliced spring onion greens for garnish

Method
1. Take a grinder jar. Add ginger, garlic, coriander stems, fresh red chillies, tomato and onion and grind to fine paste.
2. Heat oil in a nonstick kadai. Add ground paste and cook on medium heat till oil separates. 
3. Add vegetable stock and once the mixture comes to a boil, add cabbage, carrot, mushrooms and French beans and salt and cook for 5-6 minutes. Add vinegar and mix well.
4. Take noodles in serving bowl, add prepared soup, drizzle sesame oil, chilli oil, sprinkle spring onion greens and serve hot.

Phataphat style mein multigrain cheela banate hain… quick, healthy, aur full of flavour.
Kuch simple aur tasty chahiye? Yeh dish zaroor banaana.

Recipe:
Ingredients

½ cup gram flour (besan)
½ cup rice flour
½ cup finger millet (ragi) flour
½ tsp turmeric powder
½ tsp cumin powder
¾ tsp red chilli powder
Salt to taste
1 tbsp ginger- garlic paste
Oil for cooking
Green chutney as required
250 grams cottage cheese (paneer)
Mixed seeds to sprinkle
Mixed lettuce leaves as required

Method

1. Take gram flour in a bowl. Add rice flour, finger millet flour, turmeric powder, cumin powder, red chilli powder, salt, ginger garlic paste and 1¼ cups water and mix well. 
2. Heat a nonstick tawa. Add some oil and spread well.
3. Spread a ladleful of batter and cook on medium heat for 2-3 minutes.
4. Flip and cook again for 2 minutes. Flip and spread green chutney.
5. Grate cottage cheese, sprinkle salt and mixed seeds in top.
6. Place aa few lettuce leaves and fold.
7. Serve hot.
